# Instance Segmentation
Instance Segmentation with Detectron2 (2023)

### Motivation
Computer Vision is a prime technology that has a wide use of applications. A large portion of computer vision models relies on artificial neural networks to process shapes, colors, and textures to understand input images passed to them. Simply, computer vision allows machines to make sense out of visual data (Morales, 2023). This project will showcase the performance of Image segmentation on a pre-trained dataset. Image segmentation, which is an extremely important computer vision task, involves converting an image into a collection of regions of pixels that are represented by a mask or a labeled image (Mathworks.com). Well known real-world applications of image segmentation include: medical image analysis, facial recognition, and digital image analysis for autonomous vehicles. The practical usage in today’s technology in the form of image segmentation serves as the motivation behind this project.

### Research Question Statement
There are two known forms of image segmentation: semantic segmentation and instance segmentation. A semantic segmentation model does not have the capabilities to discriminate amongst instances in the same category. For instance, if an image has a category of cars, a semantic segmentation model will only recognize the car category but not the different types of cars within the category. Instance segmentation is the chosen image segmentation task of interest. According to a research article by Dr. Ying Yu, Phd candidate in computer vision and pattern recognition at the University of PLA, Shijazhuang, on the techniques and challenges of image segmentation, there are two problems with image segmentation. The first problem she states is how to define meaningful regions, as the uncertainty of visual perception and the diversity of human comprehension lead to a lack of clear definition of the objects (Yu, 2023). The subsequent problem she addresses about image segmentation is its difficulty in “effectively representing the objects in an image. The chosen neural network of interest to build the image segmentation model as well as the hyperparameters chosen to tweak the neural network may influence the challenges presented by Dr. Yu in her research article. While creating the perfect image segmentation model will take time and expertise, this project will attempt to illustrate a model that can accurately and confidently identify objects and outline them in an image at the pixel level.

Image segmentation is a complex computer vision task that can be accomplished in many ways. Image segmentation models are usually trained with large datasets with millions of images and can become computationally expensive. Our simple workstation does not have the computational power to handle those types of datasets. For the sake of time, we’ll incorporate transfer learning in our model. Niklas Donges, in his article What is Transfer Learning? Exploring the Popular Deep Learning Approach, explains that the general idea of transfer learning is to use the knowledge a model has already learned from a previous task with a lot of available labeled training data in a new task that doesn’t have much data (Donges, 2022). This will prevent us from taking the time to manipulate parameters (weights that pass input data to the following layer), unnecessarily, to learn the input data. A common approach to transfer learning is to use a pre-trained model. Commonly pre-trained neural networks used in image segmentation are Inception, ResNet, and MobileNet (Fransiska, 2019). MobileNet and Inception focus on computational cost, while ResNet focuses on computational accuracy (Fransiska, 2019). The Tensorflow and Keras packages were, unfortunately, not used during the completion of our project. There was an attempt to use Matterport’s 2017 pre-trained Mask R-CNN to build our model, which was built with Tensorflow 1, however there was an issue installing the earlier distributions of Tensorflow on our local machine. An updated version of Matterport’s 2017 build of the Mask R-CNN was found on GitHub. There was an attempt to use this version, which had been built using Tensorflow 2, however we were quickly met with another issue. Specifically, when trying to start a training instance, an AttributeError was triggered that stated “module ‘tensorflow’ has no attribute ‘placeholder’. The Tensorflow module on our local machine was accessed to address the issue, however what was thought to be a solution proved not to be. The error never went away. Additionally, it had been found that the updated version of Matterport’s Mask R-CNN was built using an NVIDIA CUDA, which we did not have on our local machine. Re-coding Matterport’s Mask R-CNN algorithm, which had thousands of lines of code, was not an option nor was adding lines of code to our locally installed versions of Tensorflow and Keras everytime code was executed. So, we were not able to train using Matterport’s Mask R-CNN. Instead of using Tensorflow and Keras, a less problematic way of performing instance segmentation on our dataset was introduced with Detectron2. During the completion of our project, we implemented the computer vision library Detectron2, which is a Facebook AI Research (FAIR) computer vision library with official documentation and a designated GitHub repository. We used an api from the library to access their model zoo on GitHub (MODEL_ZOO.md) https://github.com/facebookresearch/detectron2/blob/main/MODEL_ZOO.md which gave us access to several pre-trained models and their weights. Formally, according to the GitHub documentation, MODEL_ZOO.md is a large collection of baseline algorithms that may be referenced in separate projects. The repo states that all numbers were obtained on Facebook’s deep learning server, Big Basin, with 8 NVIDIA V100 GPUs & NVLink. The repo provided us with several COCO Instance Segmentation Baseline Models trained with Mask R-CNN. The baseline models, according to the repo, were trained with three different backbone combinations (FPN, C4, DC5). Since our time to complete the project was limited, we chose a baseline that had been trained with a Feature Pyramid Network (FPN), which would offer the fastest training time compared to others. The COCO Instance Segmentation Baselines had been trained with both a 3x schedule and a 1x schedule. The 3x schedule baselines were trained for a longer period of time than the 1x schedule baselines. Specifically, the repo documentation clarifies that 3x schedule baselines were trained for approximately 37 epochs and 1x schedule baselines were trained for approximately 12 epochs. We chose to train with the baseline that has a resnet50 + FPN backbone, was trained the longest, and comparatively had the quicker training and inference documented times. Here is the link to our chosen model: https://github.com/facebookresearch/detectron2/blob/main/configs/COCO-InstanceSegmentation/mask_rcnn_R_50_FPN_3x.yaml

Furthermore, an understanding of how a Mask R-CNN is structured is best explained by two medium articles: Simple Understanding of Mask RCNN by Xiang Zhang and Splash of Color: Instance Segmentation with Mask R-CNN and Tensorflow by Waleed Abdulla. There are two stages to the Mask R-CNN. As it is explained in lamen in Waleed Abdulla’s article, the first stage scans the input image and generates proposals, which are areas in the image that are likely to contain an object (Abdulla, 2018). The second stage will perform a classification of these proposals and generate bounding boxes and masks (Abdulla, 2018). Both of these stages are attached to a feature pyramid neural network or the backbone architecture “that consists of a bottom-up pathway, a top-bottom pathway and lateral connections” (Zhang, 2018). During the first stage, a regional proposal network (RPN) will scan the top-bottom pathway (feature map) through set of boxes, called anchors, with predefined locations and scales relative to images that will bind features to its raw image location. Then the RPN will generate proposals. The second stage of the Mask R-CNN will use another neural network that will confiscate proposed regions by the RPN in the first stage and “assign them to several specific areas of a feature map level, scans these areas, and generates objects classes (multi-categorical classified), bounding boxes and masks” (Zhang, 2018).
We developed our model on Google Colaboratory since all the preliminary packages we needed were already preinstalled. Also, in order to utilize the Detectron2 library we needed to match the dependencies of the Detectron2 library and Google Colab met the requirements, providing a pre-installed NVIDIA GPU and NVIDIA CUDA for each individual runtime. The following articles and tutorials were used to help us complete our project: The Detectron2 documentation (Welcome to Detectron2’S Documentation! — Detectron2 0.6 Documentation, n.d.), Google Colab Detectron2 Tutorial.ipynb file (Google Colaboratory, n.d.), Wendee’s Instance Segmentation with Detectron2 medium article (Wendee, 2020) to give an overview of how to implement Detectron2 in our project, Detectron2’s GitHub repository (Wu et al., 2019), Aravinda’s medium article How to split image dataset into train, validation and test set? (加阳, 2023), and Dana Rausch’s article EDA for Image Classification (Rausch, 2021).

  # Data Summary

The original tensorflow bee_dataset was changed since none of the images were appropriate for instance segmentation. All bee images contained one object (bee or wasp), which would have sufficed for semantic segmentation, however our goal was to predict the pixels of the image that belong to a particular instance. Also, the COCO dataset was not physically used like our goat dataset. Instead, Detectron2’s baseline algorithms were pre-trained on the COCO dataset so we removed this section.
The dataset of choice was a custom built dataset that consisted of 57 randomly chosen goat images from Flickr.com. This dataset is not a multi-label or multi-class dataset. However, the majority of these images contain multiple objects of interest within the same class. The features of this image dataset vary by image. There are a few reasons for this:
Some images on Flickr.com are downloadable and others are not. This preference is set by whoever uploads the image.
Our local machine is smaller in size compared to most industry workstations that perform instance segmentation tasks, so the pixel size matters. The bigger the pixel size the more RAM our local machine will use to store the image data. So image size was kept to a limit.
Image size could not be too small because when annotating images, the image of interest will need to be expanded for proper annotations. Small images expanded or heavily increased in size may expose image pixelations and annotations may then become rigid
Pixel size and width needed to be controlled in order to preserve our local machine.
